00:26:38.959 --> 00:26:44.560
kind of doing a validation exercise, which is a little different than, like, a discovery,

00:26:45.119 --> 00:26:52.239
and actually, we may not even be doing hypothesis testing, because folks often don't really want to

00:26:52.239 --> 00:26:55.680
know if we can prove or disprove that they're right. They want to, they really want to ask

00:26:55.680 --> 00:27:00.160
the question, and I apologize, my statistic language, I should be able to say this in

00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:04.880
terms of inference and what it means, and I'm hesitant to use the terms of art for fear I may

00:27:04.880 --> 00:27:12.719
misuse them, but in principle, what we're doing is we're saying, is there evidence that supports

00:27:12.719 --> 00:27:19.599
this thing we want to believe? We're not really looking to disprove it, or we may be, but usually

00:27:19.599 --> 00:27:24.959
we're just looking to say, this is our intuition, so it's almost like this is our Bayesian prior,

00:27:24.959 --> 00:27:33.359
is the data inconsistent with our prior? We're not really asking to be, to prove it, and so sometimes

00:27:33.359 --> 00:27:41.119
when we, when I get a situation like that, we go looking for evidence that supports this

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:49.199
conclusion we're starting with, and often the best we can say is, we can't really find a lot

