00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:35.359
saying non-linearity. So, there's two things that make modeling any system really hard,

00:29:36.400 --> 00:29:45.439
non-linearity and feedback effects, and those, the presence of either of those or both of them,

00:29:45.439 --> 00:29:50.800
God forbid, right? So, let's pause right here and think, what types of systems have non-linearity

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:56.959
and feedback effects? I'm an economist by training, and this is why macroeconomics always

00:29:56.959 --> 00:30:04.079
feels like a black art and not like a real set of analysis, is because there's non-linearity and

00:30:04.079 --> 00:30:08.880
feedback effects in the economy. It's tremendously hard to model. It's tremendously hard to calibrate

00:30:08.880 --> 00:30:14.000
parameters because of all the non-linearity feedback effects, lag effects, all that sort of

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:19.839
thing. Similarly, over the last three years, two years, we have all gotten a tremendous education

00:30:19.839 --> 00:30:25.359
in how hard epidemiology is, right? Those of us who couldn't even pronounce epidemiology four

00:30:25.359 --> 00:30:32.319
years ago have learned that epidemiology is full of non-linearity and feedback effects. That makes

00:30:32.319 --> 00:30:37.439
it really hard. And so, a lot of times when I've come to a data set and I'm seeing no effects that

00:30:37.439 --> 00:30:44.400
I would theorize are there, I try to think about and drill into the data and see if there's possibly

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:49.199
some non-linearity or possibly some feedback effects because both of those will mess up

00:30:49.199 --> 00:30:55.599
correlations, right? So, you may show a data that has relatively low correlation because correlation

00:30:55.599 --> 00:31:01.520
is an average across a range. It's boiling that down, the average of the relationship across a

00:31:01.520 --> 00:31:09.520
range. If that value of one variable is zero most of the time, and occasionally it's one,

00:31:10.079 --> 00:31:16.079
and the impact over here is continuous and is noise, but when this one goes to one, this one

00:31:16.079 --> 00:31:22.560
doubles, that correlation is going to look not very significant, but it may be a real meaningful

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:26.800
effect, right? So, that's kind of a, it's not a, this variable isn't linear, right? It's usually zero,

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:33.119
occasionally it's one. This one's noisy, but when this one goes to one, it doubles its range or

00:31:33.119 --> 00:31:39.359
something, right? So, that's an example of a non-linear relationship that's really hard to get linear

00:31:39.359 --> 00:31:44.319
correlations out of that tip you off to what's going on. So, sometimes I go digging in looking for those

00:31:44.319 --> 00:31:48.959
or if there's some kind of feedback effect of some combination of two variables

00:31:50.239 --> 00:31:57.680
interacting with each other is having effect you want. So, I guess that's the big picture.

