00:36:06.719 --> 00:36:11.679
average. And I'll give you an example of this very specific that we just went through in our

00:36:11.679 --> 00:36:22.080
organization that, in my mind, shows a lot of good thought. So we implemented a best practice

00:36:22.080 --> 00:36:31.679
for system passwords. So we have accounts, system accounts, and we use for our, you know,

00:36:31.679 --> 00:36:37.439
these automated processes that I talked about, we use system accounts for database access or whatever.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:49.280
And as a best practice, our ops team had a very large character set that included some particularly

00:36:49.280 --> 00:36:57.600
pernicious special characters, like ampersands, semicolons, and backslashes, I think, all produce

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:03.040
real challenges on different systems. And there's kind of some hoops you can jump through to handle

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:11.120
some of these. But the bottom line is, what you want in a password is lots of entropy. The character

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:16.080
set with a password this big and a big character set gives you a certain amount of entropy.

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:22.560
You can lower the character set and lengthen the password and get the same or more entropy.

00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:30.719
What you care about is entropy. Nobody gives a crap that there's special characters in there

00:37:30.719 --> 00:37:37.840
if you know what you're after is entropy. But best practice is use big character set. So a bunch of us

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:43.040
were having systems that were barfing when the passwords would get rotated, and we would end up

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:50.560
with like an ampersand in the password, and certain code systems were falling over on the password

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:56.080
because it was causing problems. And we went to our security team and we said, we know what, what's that?

00:37:56.719 --> 00:38:01.840
I said, quick question in between, what is entropy? So entropy is the amount of randomness, right? What we

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:06.959
really care about is how hard is it to guess. And we'll use entropy as a proxy for how hard would it

00:38:06.959 --> 00:38:14.159
be for a search loop that was going through every character and making the password. How long would

00:38:14.159 --> 00:38:19.600
it take that to guess that password? That's what we really care about. That's the thing we really

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:26.320
care about. And, but yet, you know, our best practice is, you know, eight characters and a big character

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:30.800
space. So each one of these values can be 50 different things because we include special

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:34.639
characters. You know, we went to them and said, let's take special characters out because they're

00:38:34.639 --> 00:38:40.239
causing us some pain, and let's make it really long because we don't care about length. Length is easy.

00:38:40.239 --> 00:38:44.719
It's an automated system, right? But these special characters are giving us a problem.

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:52.239
And, and our team, our ops team said, oh, that makes sense. Cool. Are we not doing best practice?

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:58.320
No. Are we accomplishing our goal? Hell yeah, we are. And we've gotten more entropy than we had

00:38:58.320 --> 00:39:03.439
when we were using the character set with the special characters because we made them a lot

00:39:03.439 --> 00:39:08.080
longer. We just use a smaller character set. So if someone's trying to brute force it, actually,

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:13.120
it's harder to brute force our passwords now with no special characters than it would have been to

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:16.239
brute force them with the special characters in there because we made them really long.

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:22.560
And that's an example of if we're using our head about what is the problem we're actually

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:28.320
trying to solve and not hiding behind, this is best practice, we get to a better outcome.

00:39:28.320 --> 00:39:32.879
And it's because we had, you know, I hate to sound like a Stephen Covey book or something,

00:39:32.879 --> 00:39:38.000
but like we started with the end in mind. What's the thing we're optimizing? We want passwords

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:43.199
that are hard to guess. All right. How do we accomplish that? Subject to the constraint of

00:39:43.199 --> 00:39:48.800
special characters are giving our systems problems. That's an example of, I think,

